<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Memorandum to the House of Commons Liaison Committee from Dr Ruth Levitt and William Solesbury, Visiting Senior Research Fellows, King’s College London, Dept of Political Economy</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> from Dr Ruth Levitt and William Solesbury, Visiting Senior Research Fellows, King’s College London, Dept of Political Economy</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> (SCE0020)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">1. Our memorandum responds to the third of the questions on which the Committee invited views from outside observers: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">What more needs to be done? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In doing so, it takes as a starting point the ‘clear vision of the future’ in Chapter 8 of</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> the Committee’s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> report on </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmliaisn/697/697.pdf"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:none">Select committee effectiveness, resources and powers</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> of 8 November 2012 (Second Report of Session 2012–13, HC 697)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, which </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">stated : </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Our aim is that committees should be respected, listened to and feared by departments and ministers for the quality of their investigations, the rigour of their questioning, the depth of their analysis, and the value of their reports…Their ability to do their job will not be limited by constraints on access to information or the witnesses they wish to hear from, and they will be able to draw</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">on expert advice and research. (Para 136)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">2. We believe that these objectives </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">need to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">take into account t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">he government’s commitment to ‘open policy making’,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">as stated in its </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Civil Service Reform Plan</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (June 2012), wh</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ich advocates a greater contribution </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">to policy development</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> from sources of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">expertise </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">utside Whitehall departments</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">3. S</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">elect committees increasingly need to identify, question and analyse these external sources </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">of expertise as an integral part of their scrutiny of ministerial and official performance</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">4. Select committees should see it as their own responsibility to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">pursu</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">this more thorough </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">’evidence trail’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (somewhat like an</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> audit trail for financial accountability</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">). C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ommittee members and their advisers need to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">enhance their knowledge and </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">skills</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> in order to evaluate and comment wisely on the ‘evidence trail’.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About the authors</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. Dr Ruth Levitt and William Solesbury </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">study </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">uses and effectiveness of the policy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">expert</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ise that ministers and departments seek from sources </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">outside Whitehall</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">policy development.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> Their earlier work includes research on</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> the contribution of outsiders brought into government departments as </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">direct </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">appointees to the Senior Civil Service, as non-executive board members and as members of policy units.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> In 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">their research on policy tsars revealed the growth in the scale and scope of such public appointments over the last four </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">administrations.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ir </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">new research</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Advising Ministers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, will </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">evaluate the effectiveness and impact of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">an even broader range of way</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">s in which expert advice is brought to bear on policy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Open policy making</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. The g</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">overnment’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Civil Service Reform Plan</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (June 2012) favoured what it termed ‘open policymaking’ and promoted greater outsourcing of policy advice as a step towards that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">Whitehall has a virtual monopoly on policy development, which means that policy is often drawn up on the basis of too narrow a range of inputs and is not subject to external challenge prior to announcement….the need to maintain a safe space for policy advice should not be used to prevent the maximum possible openness to new thinking or in the gathering of evidence and insight from external experts.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The Prime Minister, appearing before the House of Commons Liaison Committee on 3 July 2012, expressed this from a ministerial perspective:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">We should also recognise that the civil service does not have a monopoly on policy wisdom, so we have what we call policy contestability. On some occasions, we should go outside the civil service and say, ‘Here’s a particular challenge’ – for example setting up the green investment bank – ‘Can you help us O think-tank or O academic body, in developing this policy?’</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Sources of external expertise</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">advocating the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">opening up </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">policy making, the government has given no comprehensive statement of what it considers </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">to be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">the appropriate sources of outside expertise. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Of course s</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ome </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">sources </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">long </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">been in use</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, such as advisory committees, researchers, respondents to consultations</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. O</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">thers are relative newcomers, such as think tanks or policy tsars</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. Y</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">et others</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, once much more frequently used, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">have fallen out of favour, notably Royal Commissions.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">7. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Some </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">external </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">sources are commissioned on the initiative of ministers or departments to provide evidence or advice; others provide one or both on their own initiative in the hope that they will be heard.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> This is reflected in the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">following list of sources of external expertise:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">A. Minister or department initiates</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">nformal</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ad hoc, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">off the record conversations with experts</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">special political advisers, often called ‘Spads’</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">temporary civil servants, recruited for their expertise </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">independent policy advisers, often called ‘policy tsars’</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">professional advice, for example commissioned from a lawyer, economist or statistician </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">researchers or consultants commissioned by departments</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">responses to government consultations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> conferences and seminars</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">expert bodies such as scientific advisory committees, such as the Advisory Committee on the Misuse of Drugs, the National Institute of Health and</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Care Excellence (NICE)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">and the Migration Advisory Committee</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">seminars with invited experts, often called ‘summits’ </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">public inquiries. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">B. External source initiates</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">audits, inspections and scrutinies, such as the work of the National Audit Office, Ofsted or HM Inspector of Prisons</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">parliamentary inquiries and reports</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">reports and briefings from think tanks and research centres</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">lobbying by NGOs, professional, business, trade and political organisations</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">conferences and seminars convened independently.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">With ‘open policy making’ the evidential basis of policy that a select committee might wish to explore may well be drawn from </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">more than one of these </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">sources.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">8. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The utility of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">all these </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">sources should be evaluated in terms of:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">relevance (to the policy issue under consideration)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">timeliness (in relation to the policy cycle and political context)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">reliability (how well-informed and how respected the source)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">applicability (to possible courses of action) </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">and, not least important, </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">cost. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Select committee practice</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">elect committees have </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">sometimes recognised </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">external contributions to policy development</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> in their area</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Recently, f</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">or example:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">the Transport Committee called on Sam Laidlaw to give evidence about his inquiry into the failed West Coast rail franchising procedure.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">he Communities and Local Government Committee summoned Mary Portas to give evidence on her review, as a policy tsa</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, on the future of the high street.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">he Transport Select Committee </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">asked</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> consultants KPMG to defend their analysis of the econom</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">c benefits of the high speed rail project which had been commissioned from them by the Department for Transport</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">10. These exemplify a common t</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">endency </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">to examine such</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">contributions to policy </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">in isolation, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">possibly prompted </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">by newsworthy developments. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">  But </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> external sources of evidence and advice increasingly deserve attention in the more strategic, forward looking</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">scrutiny of department performance that the earlier Liaison Committee</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">’s Second R</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">eport recommended (in Chapter 4).</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This could either be in committee inquiries on a policy or in their reviews of departmental Annual Reports.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">11. </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Select committees should see it as their own responsibility to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">pursu</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">this more thorough </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">’evidence trail’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (somewhat like an</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> audit trail for financial accountability</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">). Of course the term ‘evidence trail’ should not be taken as suggesting a simple, linear relationship between evidence and policy. It is well established that evidence and policy interact and influence each other in both directions and over time.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">12</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ommittee members and their advisers</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> need </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">develop their skills to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">adopt a more ‘forensic’ approach</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> in order</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> to identify and question the evidential basis of department</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">s’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> polic</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ies and policy intentions, from whatever source</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ommittees’ research funding </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">may perhaps be </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">used to this end.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">15 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">Evidence-informed policy: what difference do outsiders in Whitehall make? </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">ESRC UK Centre for Evidence Based Policy and Practice, Working Paper 23, 2005</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">;  </span><a href="http://www.kcl.ac.uk/sspp/departments/politicaleconomy/research/cep/pubs/papers/assets/wp23.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.kcl.ac.uk/sspp/departments/politicaleconomy/research/cep/pubs/papers/assets/wp23.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> Policy tsars: here to stay but more transparency needed, King’s College London</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">2012</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">; </span><a href="http://www.kcl.ac.uk/sspp/departments/politicaleconomy/research/tsarsreport/Tsars-Final-Report-Dec-2012.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.kcl.ac.uk/sspp/departments/politicaleconomy/research/tsarsreport/Tsars-Final-Report-Dec-2012.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> HM Government, The Civil Service Reform Plan, June 2012, p. 14.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> House of Commons Liaison Committee, Oral evidence from the Prime Minister, 3 July 2012, Q60, Session 2012-13, HC 484-i.</span></p></body></html>